ABUJA – President Muhammadu Buhari who is away in the United Kingdom undergoing some medical checks, has broken his silence on the crisis rocking the All Progressive Congress. The President who spoke through his media aide, Garba Shehu, on Saturday in Abuja, warned the leaders (and membership) of the party to desist from name-calling and backstabbing ahead of the oncoming March 26 Convention. He also cautioned them on the need to remain steadfast and maintain its unity if the party is to continue in the path of victory and its dominance at all levels throughout the country. Constitution Review: What Nigerian Women Want –Women Groups We’ve Taken Out Most Self-Acclaimed Terror Leaders –Air Marshal… The President used the prominent opposition party, the Peoples Democratic Party, to buttress his point, urging members to look at the once-powerful now enfeebled and adrift and learn lessons in disunity, mismanagement and corruption. ”They failed in 16 years in power and a failure as opposition. “Yes, we are entitled to our own share of dissent and intra-party discord. These are common in all parties, left and right all over the world. “But parties splintered by competing egos destine themselves to the worst possible fate,” the President warned. ”As the country prepares for the long run up to the 2023 presidential election, we all expect a robust debate on the issues that matter and what is going in the APC should be a reflection of this, not the infighting we are seeing. POLL “There must be no more distractions ahead of the convention to choose new leaders.”